textDisplay: The funny thing is... I recall back when I was little ('90s-early '00s) that children's stations (like PBS and Sesame Street) had PSA's about shots, vaccinations, etc. I was petrified of getting shots and would pass out or vomit at the sight of a needle when I was little. I think a show that will show everything's going to be ok, and it's not as bad as you think is a good thing. Like, why, all of a sudden, are vaccines 'the devil'? We've had mandatory vaccines for as long as I can remember. They require you to be vaccinated or at least have a reasonable excuse (i.e., allergic to a vaccine) to not be vaccinated in order to attend public school and university. I think that started in the early 20th century, and there are at least 8 vaccines are required (with immunization records as proof). This is a good thing. We don't need a bunch of kids getting deadly or debilitating diseases for something entirely preventable (i.e., polio, measles, etc.) It takes a deranged mentality to think vaccines don't provide a benefit to the framework of society.

textDisplay: 1:29:44 a crazy example of labor militancy that I'm not sure how well known it is around the country is the Homestead strike. In Pittsburgh during the steel days Carnegie Steel reduced pay for every worker in the mill without negotiating with the union. Every single worker went on strike and blocked the entrance into the mill so no new employees could be hired. Carnegie and Frick, the two main shareholders of the mill, hired a group that was known to break up strikes. The group and workers literally went to war with guns and cannons when the group attempted to approach the mill by boats on the river near by. I think like 12 or 15 people died and the group the owners hired surrendered.

textDisplay: I work in a dog grooming shop and we were having people pick up and drop off out in our parking lot for a bit at the beginning of Covid. It was basically like carside service. We also had strict guidelines to follow in order to not get reported to the public health office because numbers were through the roof in MO at the time. textDisplay:
Conservatism is a disease. What it all boils down to is hate. Can’t “teach” kids that being gay is ok, that’s communism. I put teach in quotes there because it doesn’t matter if you’re bringing up homosexuality to say it’s okay or just mentioning it in passing, anything that could make a person under the age of 18 aware that being gay is even a thing that happens is commie propaganda and you’re trying to convert children. You can’t teach children about slavery or the lasting effect it’s had on black people, because our children are strong independent thinkers who can do anything, yet so fragile at the same time that the thought that America wasn’t always so exceptional as some want to believe is just too much for their poor poor children to bear.

There’s no room for nuance in modern day conservatism. You’re either for everything they “stand” for (Not much policy there, as much as just standing against the libs, or crying foul when culture moves too far away from puritanical christian and American exceptionalist values.) or you’re a communist, fascist (pot meet kettle), who believes America should be like Soviet Russia circa the Cold War or communist China or Venezuela where they’re eating rats.

The truth is, we liberals, just want affordable (or free) healthcare, a more robust social safety net so that nobody has to pull themselves up by their bootstraps or die trying, and a more just and fair society to everyone involved including those same republicans who hate us for it. Some of those benefits would include free post-secondary education (well, free as in taxed like k-12 school) more mandatory vacation and sick time at work, maternity and paternity leave, free or low cost childcare, etc. I’m not saying that doesn’t come with some minor drawbacks for certain groups, mainly white men like myself who have had more power than everyone else our entire lives, even if we didn’t realize it. Yes, some of our lives are hard and we’ve worked hard and certainly don’t feel privileged, but that doesn’t change that if a black woman were in our same position in life she wouldn’t have a harder time of getting where we did. Other drawbacks would hit the rich, who would at minimum have to pay the same percentage as everyone else (not 0-5% which is what most pay through untaxed borrowing against stock portfolios, taking stock options rather than actual monetary pay, and various other loopholes.) Oh, and policy to safeguard against climate change and grow green energy faster and ensure our grid is rebuilt to handle it and robust enough to be maintained well into the future.

The sad thing is, all of this leads to a better future for republicans than what they’re trying to achieve right now. Now, if we could just get them to realize they’re not a few good decisions and lucky breaks from being a millionaire/billionaire (you’re not) and that most of this will never meaningfully impact their day to day lives negatively, and in fact will impact them positively… many likely still wouldn’t be on board because they just hate either minorities, immigrants, or non-cishet and the thought that they could be treated well makes them mad and they’d rather give up a better life for themselves than see others achieve it… but I think enough would be to make a difference.

Didn’t show up to training lol
